presentation.heroDescription: Industrial & Data Centre REIT • A$86B AUM • 5.0 GW Power Bank
presentation.heroCompanyDescription: Goodman Group (ASX: GMG) is a global integrated property group that owns, develops, and manages industrial real estate and data centres across 14 countries. Originally a logistics-focused REIT, Goodman is rapidly transforming into the world's largest listed data centre developer, with 57% of its A$12.9B development pipeline dedicated to hyperscaler data centre facilities.

skew.rationale: Data centre mega-trend provides visible multi-year earnings growth. 5.0 GW power bank across 13 cities is a globally unique asset. A$12.9B development WIP is 94% pre-committed. CPP Investments A$14B European DC partnership validates platform value. Forward P/E of 23.7x reasonable for growth profile.

verdict.text: Goodman is executing a generational transformation from industrial REIT to global data centre infrastructure platform. The 5.0 GW power bank across 13 cities is a moat that cannot be replicated quickly. A$12.9B in development WIP (57% data centres, rising to 75% by FY26) is 94% pre-committed to hyperscalers. CPP Investments' A$14B European DC partnership validates the platform at institutional scale. Operating EPS grew 9.8% to 118.0 cents with FY26 guidance for further 9% growth. At 36.2x trailing P/E (23.7x forward), the market is paying a premium but the earnings visibility is exceptional.

narrative.theNarrative: The market narrative centres on whether Goodman is a property company that does data centres, or a data centre infrastructure platform that happens to own property. At 36.2x trailing P/E and 3.3x book, the market is paying a significant premium to traditional REIT valuations. The embedded thesis is that Goodman's 5.0 GW power bank, hyperscaler relationships, and A$12.9B development pipeline represent a structurally differentiated platform that justifies the premium. The stock is 17% off its 52-week high, reflecting concerns about data centre oversupply narratives and rising interest rates pressuring REIT valuations.

priceImplication.label: Embedded Assumptions at A$30.76
priceImplication.content: DC demand sustains: Hyperscaler capex continues at current or higher levels for 3-5 years. Execution flawless: A$12.9B WIP delivers on time and budget; 94% pre-commitment rate holds. Power procurement succeeds: 5.0 GW power bank translates to operational capacity without grid bottlenecks. Platform premium justified: 36.2x P/E sustained by data centre growth narrative rather than traditional REIT yields. Institutional capital flows: CPP deal is the first of many institutional DC partnerships.

narrative.evidenceCheck: The bull thesis has strong empirical support. FY25 delivered operating EPS of 118.0 cents (+9.8%), AUM of A$86B, and 96.5% occupancy. The CPP Investments A$14B European data centre partnership is institutional validation at scale. The 94% pre-commitment rate on A$12.9B WIP means the near-term pipeline is contracted, not speculative. FY26 guidance for operating EPS growth of 9% and operating profit exceeding A$2.6B provides visible forward earnings. The bear arguments (oversupply, power constraints, valuation) exist but lack near-term evidence.
narrative.narrativeStability: Stable and favourable. The data centre narrative is reinforced by each new hyperscaler commitment, institutional partnership, and power bank expansion announcement. The narrative is most vulnerable to a macro shock (hyperscaler capex cut, recession-driven demand slowdown) or execution failure (project delays, power grid constraints). Greg Goodman's 27-year tenure provides leadership stability uncommon in the sector.

evidence.intro: Ten evidence domains assessed. Evidence strongly favours T1 (Data Centre Mega-Trend), with limited near-term support for the bearish hypotheses.

cards.title: 1. Corporate Communications
cards.finding: FY25 results: operating EPS 118.0 cents (+9.8%), operating profit A$2,311M (+13%), AUM A$86B. Management framing: data centres as the "defining opportunity" for the next decade. CPP Investments A$14B European DC partnership announced as validation of platform model. Pipeline guidance: WIP to rise from A$12.9B to A$17.5B, with data centres comprising 75% by FY26 (up from 57%). Power bank expanded to 5.0 GW across 13 cities. 300MW under construction with target of 500MW. Distribution of 30.0 cents maintained.
cards.tension: Management is understandably promotional about the DC opportunity, but the key metrics are independently verifiable in statutory filings. The tension is between the genuine strength of the DC pipeline (contracted, pre-committed) and the question of whether Goodman is over-concentrating in a single theme. The shift from 57% DC to 75% by FY26 is a significant strategic bet on one sector.
cards.source: FY25 Results presentation; ASX announcements; Investor Day materials

cards.title: 2. Regulatory Filings
cards.finding: FY25 (audited): Revenue A$2,311M (+16.5%). Operating profit A$2,311M (+13%). Operating EPS 118.0 cents (+9.8%). NTA per share A$9.44. Gearing 4.3% (among lowest in global REIT sector). AUM A$86B with A$72B external. Development WIP A$12.9B across 57 projects, 94% pre-committed. Occupancy 96.5%. Distribution per share 30.0 cents. Debt/equity 0.23x. No material audit qualifications. A$4B capital raising successfully completed, supporting pipeline expansion.
cards.source: GMG FY25 Annual Report; ASX filings; audited financial statements

cards.title: 3. Broker Research
cards.finding: Strongly bullish consensus. 11 analysts rate Buy, 0 rate Sell. Median 12-month target A$37-38, implying 22-24% upside from current price. Broker thesis centres on data centre pipeline, power bank as competitive moat, and institutional capital attraction. Morningstar fair value estimate A$29 is the conservative outlier. Key debate among brokers is whether the DC premium is sustainable or whether GMG should be valued as a traditional REIT (implying significant downside).
cards.tension: The broker consensus is overwhelmingly bullish, but the Morningstar A$29 estimate represents a credible alternative view that traditional REIT valuation frameworks should apply. The gap between consensus targets (A$37-38) and Morningstar (A$29) reflects the fundamental disagreement about whether GMG is a property company or an infrastructure platform.
cards.source: UBS, Macquarie, Morgan Stanley, Goldman Sachs, Morningstar consensus data

cards.title: 4. Competitor & Industry Data
cards.finding: Goodman's power bank is the key differentiator. Global data centre REITs (Equinix, Digital Realty) and hyperscalers (AWS, Microsoft, Google) are all expanding DC capacity, but Goodman's 5.0 GW power bank across 13 cities is a uniquely scarce asset. Power access is the binding constraint for DC development globally; having secured power in advance gives Goodman a 3-5 year time advantage. Equinix trades at ~70x forward P/E; Digital Realty at ~45x. Goodman's 23.7x forward P/E is a discount to pure DC peers despite similar or superior growth.
cards.source: Equinix, Digital Realty filings; CBRE DC market reports; JLL industrial data

cards.title: 5. Economic Data
cards.finding: Global data centre demand growing at 25-30% annually, driven by AI training and inference workloads, cloud migration, and digital transformation. Power availability is the binding constraint: grid capacity limitations in key markets (Northern Virginia, Singapore, Dublin) are creating a premium for developers who have secured power in advance. Interest rates remain elevated, pressuring REIT valuations broadly, but institutional capital is flowing into data centre infrastructure as a distinct asset class. Global DC market estimated at US$350B+ by 2030.
cards.source: IEA power demand forecasts; CBRE data centre reports; RBA; central bank data

cards.title: 6. Alternative Data
cards.finding: Hiring patterns confirm DC pivot. LinkedIn data shows Goodman aggressively recruiting data centre engineers, power procurement specialists, and critical infrastructure managers. Job postings have shifted materially from traditional industrial property roles toward DC-specific technical roles. Employee count remains lean at ~1,030 (A$83M AUM per employee), suggesting high operational efficiency. No negative Glassdoor signals. Web traffic to Goodman's DC-specific pages has increased significantly.
cards.source: LinkedIn job postings; Glassdoor; SimilarWeb; employee review sites

cards.title: 7. Academic Research
cards.finding: Academic literature on data centre economics confirms several key structural dynamics. Power access is the primary competitive moat: research on DC site selection shows that power availability, not land or construction capability, determines competitive advantage. Studies on AI compute demand project exponential growth in training and inference workloads through at least 2035. Real estate platform economics research shows that integrated develop-own-manage models generate superior returns to pure development or pure ownership strategies.
cards.source: Data centre economics journals; AI compute demand research; real estate platform studies

cards.title: 8. Media & Social
cards.finding: Media coverage is predominantly positive, framing Goodman as the "data centre REIT play" on the ASX. Periodic bearish commentary focuses on data centre oversupply fears and REIT valuation multiples. Social media sentiment is moderately bullish. The "data centre bubble" narrative appears in broader market commentary but is rarely applied specifically to Goodman, given its pre-committed pipeline. Financial press coverage of the CPP partnership was overwhelmingly positive.
cards.source: Australian Financial Review; Bloomberg; ASX investment forums

cards.title: 9. Leadership & Governance
cards.finding: Exceptional founder-led governance with deep skin in the game. Greg Goodman co-founded the company in 1998 and has served as CEO for 27+ years. His ~1.82% shareholding is worth approximately A$747M at current prices, creating complete alignment with shareholders. Under his leadership, Goodman has grown from an Australian industrial property trust to a A$63.4B global platform. The strategic pivot from pure industrial REIT to data centre infrastructure developer is Goodman's defining bet, and it was made earlier than competitors. Danny Breslin (CIO) and Jason Little (COO) provide strong operational depth. The board includes experienced property and infrastructure directors. Key strength: long tenure, consistent strategy, and a lean organisation. Key risk: succession planning for a 27-year CEO is the obvious long-term question, though not an immediate concern.
cards.source: GMG Annual Report FY25; ASX filings; board biographical disclosures

cards.title: 10. Ownership & Capital Flows
cards.finding: Institutional quality register with growing passive allocation. Goodman's register reflects its ASX 20 status: dominated by large institutional holders and index funds. Founder Greg Goodman's 1.82% stake (A$747M) is the key alignment signal. Institutional ownership is high and stable; the A$4B capital raising in FY25 was well-supported, indicating institutional appetite for the DC growth story. Short interest is low at ~1-2% of free float, suggesting limited bearish conviction. The register has shifted incrementally toward global infrastructure and DC-specialist funds, reflecting the market's gradual reclassification of GMG from pure REIT to infrastructure platform. No substantial holder has filed a reduction notice recently.
cards.source: ASX substantial holder notices; ASIC short position reports; annual report top-20; capital raising disclosures

tripwires.intro: Four revision conditions. Data centre pipeline execution is the single most important variable for hypothesis revision.

cards.name: Half-Year Operating Performance

conditions.then: T1 strengthens. Execution on track; DC pipeline expanding as guided. Growth flywheel confirmed.

conditions.if: If operating EPS growth <7% or WIP growth stalls
conditions.then: T2 strengthens. Growth narrative weakening; market premium at risk.

cards.source: Source: ASX announcement; GMG half-year results

cards.name: Hyperscaler Capex Announcements

conditions.then: T3 strengthens sharply. First evidence of demand deceleration. DC oversupply narrative gains credibility.

cards.source: Source: Microsoft, Alphabet, Amazon quarterly earnings; capex disclosures

conditions.then: T1 execution confirmed. Power moat deepening.

conditions.if: If material construction delays or power grid bottlenecks disclosed

cards.source: Source: GMG quarterly updates; energy regulator approvals; ASX announcements

couldntAssess: Hyperscaler contract terms: The specific terms, pricing, and duration of Goodman's data centre leases with hyperscalers are commercially confidential. Whether Goodman's DC yields are superior or inferior to competitors' is not publicly available.

Power procurement costs: The cost of securing 5.0 GW of power across 13 cities is not broken out in financial statements. Whether power costs are escalating faster than DC rental yields would be material to margin analysis.

CEO succession planning: Greg Goodman is 27+ years into his tenure. While there is no immediate succession concern, the absence of a disclosed succession plan creates long-term uncertainty for a company whose strategy and culture are deeply founder-led.
gaps.analyticalLimitations: Hypothesis survival scores (T1: 38%, T2: 24%, T3: 17%, T4: 21%) reflect the strong evidence asymmetry in this case. T1 (Data Centre Mega-Trend) scores highest because the supporting evidence spans 7 of 10 domains and includes both independently verified facts (audited financials, 94% pre-commitment) and forward-looking indicators (hyperscaler capex trends, power bank expansion). T3 (Bubble Risk) scores lowest because it is driven by narrative rather than observable data: the 94% pre-commitment rate directly contradicts the oversupply thesis for Goodman's specific pipeline.
